Narrative 1

To create my data frame, Stopped, of the lyrics of Grammy nominated song with a decade variable and filtered out stop_words, I was required to use many functions. After scraping the data tables from the Wikipedia Page, I used the function rename() to change the name of Artist(s) to artist, Record to track, and Year[I] to year in each table. I also utilized the na.omit() to remove the NA values in the tables. Lastly, I removed the footnote reference numbers from the year column by utilizing the across argument for the mutate function which I found from google, mutate(across(). After the data was cleaned in each table, I then began adding the lyrics using the [genius] package and the add_genius() function. Once this was completed, I performed a full_join() on the table for the 1980s to the table for the 1990s and then I used another full_join() on this new table to the one for the 2000s, and finally I used another full_join() on this newly created table to the one for the 2010s. After the data was joined into one table, all that was left to do was filter out the stop_words. To accomplish this, I utilized the function c() to create a vector of all the words in the stop_words data table. I then created a new data frame with only one variable, named word, that contained each of these 11 stop_words. I then used the unnest_tokens() function on the large data frame to separate the lyrics into individual words and then I was able to perform the anti_join() function on the large data frame with the lyrics and the one with the stop_words.

Narrative 2: Graph 1

Graph 1 is a graph of Boxplots of Words per Grammy Nominated Song by Decade. In the graph, there is an individual boxplot to represent each decade respectively. These boxplots represent a plot of how many words in a song for each song in a decade. These boxplots are a standardized way of displaying the distribution of data based on the minimum(lowest dot), first quartile(lowest side of each box), median(line in the middle of each box), third quartile(top line of each box), and maximum(top line of each box). For example, the maximum words in a grammy nominated song in the 1980s was around 625, whereas the median words in a grammy nominated song in the 2000s was around 325.

Narrative 5: Graph 4

Graph 4 is a little more complex than Graph 3 and Graph 2. For Graph 4, the Net Sentiment Score by Year is displayed and what this means is that after the lyrics were separated into word, they were each given a positive or negative rating in regards to their sentiment. Then a sentiment score was produced which assigned all of the words a value based on their sentiment. All those words which received a positive rating received a value of 1. All those words which received a negative rating received a value of 0. Once this was complete the net sentiment was calculated which was a sum of the sentiment scores for each year. In this graph, each year is displayed with the corresponding net sentiment value for that year. The graph was grouped to show the difference in decades.

Graph 5

Narrative 6: Graph 5

Graph 5 is a display of the Mean Sentiment Score by Decade. Unlike Graph 4, this time the mean sentiment score is calculated instead of the net sentiment score and the scores for each decade are shown instead of each year. A mean is basically the sum of all the sentiment scores for that decade and then divided by the number of scores that are present.
